commit 0636b8543d3f2ba59f637b8c56febc2227ecd520
Author: Hui Zhu <zhuhui@kylinos.cn>

mm/memcontrol: batch memcg charging in __memcg_slab_post_alloc_hook

This commit batches the memcg charging in __memcg_slab_post_alloc_hook() by
scanning ahead to find contiguous objects on slabs sharing the same pgdat.

> diff --git a/mm/memcontrol.c b/mm/memcontrol.c
> --- a/mm/memcontrol.c
> +++ b/mm/memcontrol.c

[ ... ]

> -	for (i = 0; i < size; i++) {
> +	for (i = 0; i < size; ) {
>  		unsigned long obj_exts;
>  		struct slabobj_ext *obj_ext;
>  		struct obj_stock_pcp *stock;
> +		struct pglist_data *pgdat;
> +		unsigned int batch_bytes;
> +		size_t run_len = 0;

If a caller requests a large bulk allocation, could batch_bytes silently
truncate here?

obj_size and run_len are both size_t, but batch_bytes is an unsigned int.
If the total size exceeds UINT_MAX, the truncation could lead to severely
undercharging the memcg upon allocation and underflowing it upon free.

[ ... ]

> +		batch_bytes = obj_size * run_len;
>  		stock = trylock_stock();
> -		if (!stock || !__consume_obj_stock(objcg, stock, obj_size)) {
> +		if (!stock || !__consume_obj_stock(objcg, stock, batch_bytes)) {

[ ... ]

> -		__account_obj_stock(objcg, stock, obj_size,
> -				    slab_pgdat(slab), cache_vmstat_idx(s));
> +		__account_obj_stock(objcg, stock, batch_bytes,
> +				    pgdat, cache_vmstat_idx(s));

Could passing the combined batch_bytes to __account_obj_stock() corrupt the
node vmstat counters?

__account_obj_stock() takes an int for the nr parameter:

static void __account_obj_stock(struct obj_cgroup *objcg,
				struct obj_stock_pcp *stock, int nr,
				struct pglist_data *pgdat, enum node_stat_item idx)

If batch_bytes exceeds INT_MAX, nr would become negative, subtracting
from the global node counters during allocation instead of adding to them.

Additionally, does this bypass the flush thresholds for large batches?

Inside __account_obj_stock(), the local per-CPU cache is updated like this:

	if (!*bytes) {
		*bytes = nr;
		nr = 0;
	} else {
		*bytes += nr;
		if (abs(*bytes) > PAGE_SIZE) {

When nr was a single object size, the empty cache check safely stored a
small amount of bytes. With nr now representing the entire batch_bytes, a
multi-megabyte batch allocation could be deposited directly into the
per-CPU cache and hidden from the global memory statistics because the
PAGE_SIZE threshold check is skipped when the cache is initially empty.

Could this leave massive amounts of memory unrecorded in the global stats
until another allocation happens to flush it?

