```c
batch_bytes = obj_size * run_len;
```
If `run_len` is 1048576, and `obj_size` is 4096, `batch_bytes` will be `4294967296` which is `0` when truncated to 32-bit `unsigned int`. Then `__consume_obj_stock` will be called with `nr_bytes = 0`. It will succeed (if `stock->nr_bytes >= 0`). And it will subtract 0. So no charging happens!
Wait! Does `__obj_cgroup_charge` fail?
If `__consume_obj_stock` succeeds, `__obj_cgroup_charge` is bypassed!
```c
		stock = trylock_stock();
		if (!stock || !__consume_obj_stock(objcg, stock, batch_bytes)) {
			// ...
		}
		__account_obj_stock(objcg, stock, batch_bytes,
				    pgdat, cache_vmstat_idx(s));
		unlock_stock(stock);
```
So we successfully charged `0` bytes!
Wait, the `batch_bytes` is also passed to `__account_obj_stock` which takes `int nr`?
Let's see `__account_obj_stock`:
```c
static void __account_obj_stock(struct obj_cgroup *objcg,
				struct obj_stock_pcp *stock, int nr,
				struct pglist_data *pgdat, enum node_stat_item idx)
```
Wait, `__account_obj_stock` takes `int nr` !
If `batch_bytes` is `0`, `nr` is `0`.
If `batch_bytes` is `2147483648` (2 GB), it becomes negative `-2147483648` in `int`.
Then `__account_obj_stock` will add negative values to the vmstat counters!

Wait! Does `kmem_cache_alloc_bulk` allow such huge sizes?
Yes, `msm_iommu_pagetable_prealloc_allocate` calls `kmem_cache_alloc_bulk` with `p->count` which comes from user?
If it's possible to pass a size of millions, this is a clear vulnerability or bug!
However, even if `size` is just 1,000,000. `obj_size` is up to 8192 (or more).
8192 * 1000000 = 8,192,000,000 > 4,294,967,295. So yes, it overflows `unsigned int`.

Is `batch_bytes` overflow realistically reachable?
Can `kmem_cache_alloc_bulk` take a `size` that large?
`kvmalloc_array` uses `size_t`.
`kmem_cache_alloc_bulk` takes `size_t size`.
Is there a system limit? `kmem_cache_alloc_bulk_noprof` does not limit `size`.
Wait!
```c
int kmem_cache_alloc_bulk_noprof(struct kmem_cache *s, gfp_t flags, size_t size, void **p)
```
In `mm/slub.c` `kmem_cache_alloc_bulk_noprof`:
```c
	if (!size)
		return 0;

	s = slab_pre_alloc_hook(s, flags);
	if (unlikely(!s))
		return 0;

	i = alloc_from_pcs_bulk(s, flags, size, p);
```
If `size` is very large, it will allocate until memory is exhausted. But wait, before that it allocates the array of pointers `void **p`. `p` needs to be allocated. `msm_iommu` uses `kvmalloc_objs` which is `kvmalloc_array`. `kvmalloc` can allocate very large memory.
So yes, a large bulk size is possible.
If `batch_bytes` is `unsigned int`, an overflow is possible!
Wait, what if we just use `size_t batch_bytes;`?
This is a very obvious regression.
Why was it made `unsigned int`?
Because `__consume_obj_stock` takes `unsigned int nr_bytes` !
Let's check `__consume_obj_stock` in the pre-fetched context:
```c
static bool __consume_obj_stock(struct obj_cgroup *objcg,
				struct obj_stock_pcp *stock,
				unsigned int nr_bytes)
```
Wait, `__consume_obj_stock` takes `unsigned int nr_bytes`!
And `__obj_cgroup_charge` takes `size_t size` !
```c
static int __obj_cgroup_charge(struct obj_cgroup *objcg, gfp_t gfp,
			       size_t size, size_t *remainder)
```
And `__account_obj_stock` takes `int nr` !
```c
static void __account_obj_stock(struct obj_cgroup *objcg,
				struct obj_stock_pcp *stock, int nr,
				struct pglist_data *pgdat, enum node_stat_item idx)
```
